ğŸ  Types of Cloud Deployment Model
âœ´ï¸ Private Cloud: Built and owned by a single organization within their data center; not shared externally.
âœ´ï¸ Public Cloud: Provided by third parties (e.g., Amazon, Microsoft, Rackspace); accessible to anyone; scalable and cost-effective.
âœ´ï¸ Hybrid Cloud: Combines private and public clouds; e.g., internal resources for sensitive data, public for overflow or global access.
âœ´ï¸ Community Cloud: Shared by multiple organizations with similar goals; reduces costs by pooling resources for a private-like setup.

ğŸ§± Cloud Service ModelsğŸ§±
There are three main types of cloud service models, each providing different levels of control and management:

ğŸ“› Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS): Provides raw hardware resources (e.g., servers, storage, networking); the user manages OS, applications, and data.
â‡ï¸ Example: Hosting a web server on Amazon EC2; the user deploys their own software.
âœ³ï¸ User Responsibility: OS, middleware, runtime, data, applications.

ğŸ“› Platform as a Service (PaaS):
 Offers a platform for building applications; includes tools and frameworks; the user focuses on app development and data.
â‡ï¸ Example: Salesforce.com for custom app building with pre-built modules.
âœ³ï¸ User Responsibility: Applications and data.

ğŸ“› Software as a Service (SaaS): Fully managed applications delivered over the internet; no installation or maintenance needed.
â‡ï¸ Examples: Google Mail, Microsoft 365; the user just logs in and uses.
âœ³ï¸ User Responsibility: Minimal (e.g., data input); provider handles everything else.

